<subSubSection pageId="46" pageNumber="47" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="46.[151,1436,1792,1997]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,467,1792,1817]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Differential Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The dorsal habitus of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Perkins" authorityYear="2012" box="[726,883,1794,1817]" class="Insecta" family="Epimetopidae" genus="Epimetopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="peruvianus">
<emphasis box="[726,883,1794,1817]" italics="true" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">E. peruvianus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is very similar to that of 
<taxonomicName box="[1176,1319,1793,1817]" class="Insecta" family="Epimetopidae" genus="Epimetopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="angulatus">
<emphasis box="[1176,1319,1793,1817]" italics="true" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">E. angulatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1336,1431,1793,1817]" captionStart="FIGURE 78" captionStartId="42.[151,250,2001,2024]" captionTargetBox="[178,1411,492,1965]" captionTargetId="figure-90@42.[151,1436,471,1978]" captionTargetPageId="42" captionText="FIGURE 78. Epimetopus angulatus holotype, dorsal and lateral habitus, and perpendicular to pronotum." pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Figs. 78</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[151,182,1829,1853]" captionStart="FIGURE 82" captionStartId="46.[151,250,1726,1749]" captionTargetBox="[222,1370,226,1674]" captionTargetId="figure-140@46.[195,1393,193,1705]" captionTargetPageId="46" captionText="FIGURE 82. Epimetopus peruvianus holotype, dorsal and lateral habitus, and perpendicular to pronotum." pageId="46" pageNumber="47">82</figureCitation>
); 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Perkins" authorityYear="2012" box="[203,358,1830,1853]" class="Insecta" family="Epimetopidae" genus="Epimetopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="peruvianus">
<emphasis box="[203,358,1830,1853]" italics="true" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">E. peruvianus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is slightly smaller (ca. 2.62 vs. 
<quantity box="[713,817,1829,1853]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.73" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" unit="mm" value="2.73">2.73 mm</quantity>
). Reliable determinations will be based on examination of the aedeagi of the two species (
<figureCitation box="[533,668,1865,1889]" captionStart="FIGURES79–80" captionStartId="44.[151,258,1995,2018]" captionTargetBox="[366,1220,525,1983]" captionTargetId="figure-149@44.[347,1239,515,1999]" captionTargetPageId="44" captionText="FIGURES79–80. Epimetopus angulatus aedeagus,holotype.79.Detail of apex of median lobe.80.Aedeagus (after Fikáček et al.2011)." pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Figs. 79, 80</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[680,712,1865,1889]" captionStart="FIGURE 82" captionStartId="46.[151,250,1726,1749]" captionTargetBox="[222,1370,226,1674]" captionTargetId="figure-140@46.[195,1393,193,1705]" captionTargetPageId="46" captionText="FIGURE 82. Epimetopus peruvianus holotype, dorsal and lateral habitus, and perpendicular to pronotum." pageId="46" pageNumber="47">82</figureCitation>
). The aedeagus clearly differs from that of other members of the 
<emphasis box="[151,243,1901,1925]" italics="true" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Mendeli</emphasis>
group: the distal part of the median lobe is deeply divided into two processes that diverge from one another; the membranous part of the median lobe is very wide; and the parameres are wide at the base, but abruptly narrowed at about midlength, and from there to the apices are parallel.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
